We will be using 304 samples for training and 100 samples for validation.

Standardize the data¶

We will standardize the data using the mean and standard deviation of the training set. Note that we will use the mean and standard deviation of the training set to standardize the validation set.

In [3]:
mean = x_train.mean(axis=0) # mean and standard deviation computed from training set only
std = x_train.std(axis=0)
x_train -= mean
x_train /= std
x_test -= mean
x_test /= std
x_val -= mean
x_val /= std
y_train /= 1e5
y_test /= 1e5
y_val /= 1e5

Create models¶

We will try 3 models:

  • A model with 2 hidden layer with 64 neurons each
  • A model with 2 hidden layer with 128 neurons each
  • A model with 3 hidden layer with 64 neurons each
In [4]:
model1label = "Simpler network"
model1 = Sequential([
    Input(shape=(8,)),
    Dense(64, activation='relu'),
    Dense(64, activation='relu'),
    Dense(1)
])

model2label = "Deeper network"
model2 = Sequential([
    Input(shape=(8,)),
    Dense(128, activation='relu'),
    Dense(64, activation='relu'),
    Dense(1)
])

model3label="Wider network"
model3 = Sequential([
    Input(shape=(8,)),
    Dense(256, activation='relu'),
    Dense(128, activation='relu'),
    Dense(64, activation='relu'),
    Dense(1)
])

labels = [model1label, model2label, model3label]
models = [model1, model2, model3]

# configure the learning algorithm
# use same metrics for all models
for model in models:
    model.compile(optimizer='adam',loss='mse',metrics=['mae'])
    model.summary()

Train the models¶

We will train the models for 500 epochs and use the validation set to determine the best model. We will also use early stopping to stop training if the validation loss doesn't improve for 50 epochs.

In [5]:
# Train model 1
history1 = model1.fit(x_train, y_train, epochs=500, batch_size=32, validation_data=(x_val, y_val), verbose=0)

# Train model 2
history2 = model2.fit(x_train, y_train, epochs=500, batch_size=32, validation_data=(x_val, y_val), verbose=0)

# Train model 3
history3 = model3.fit(x_train, y_train, epochs=500, batch_size=32, validation_data=(x_val, y_val), verbose=0)

Evaluate the models¶

Plot the training and validation loss for each model to visualize the training process and determine if the model is overfitting. Plot the MAE of the models aswell. We will discard few epochs to get a better visualization of the model metrics. We will evaluate the models using the test set and compare the results to determine the best model.

In [6]:
# Epochs to discard
mae_discard = 10
loss_discard = 10

# Plot training and validation loss for each model
plt.figure(figsize=(18, 6))

for i, history in enumerate([history1, history2, history3], 1):
    plt.subplot(1, 3, i)
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'][loss_discard:], label='Training Loss')
    plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'][loss_discard:], label='Validation Loss')
    plt.title(f'Model {i}: '+labels[i-1])
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.ylabel('Loss')
    plt.legend()

# Plot training and validation MAE for each model
plt.figure(figsize=(18, 6))

for i, history in enumerate([history1, history2, history3], 1):
    plt.subplot(1, 3, i)
    plt.plot(history.history['mae'][mae_discard:], label='Training MAE')
    plt.plot(history.history['val_mae'][mae_discard:], label='Validation MAE')
    plt.title(f'Model {i}: '+labels[i-1])
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.ylabel('MAE')
    plt.legend() 

plt.show()

# Evaluate the models using the test set
test_loss1, test_mae1 = model1.evaluate(x_test, y_test, verbose=0)
test_loss2, test_mae2 = model2.evaluate(x_test, y_test, verbose=0)
test_loss3, test_mae3 = model3.evaluate(x_test, y_test, verbose=0)

Choose the best model¶

We will choose the model with the lowest validation loss as the best model.

In [7]:
# Extract the validation losses for each model
val_loss1 = min(history1.history['val_loss'])
val_loss2 = min(history2.history['val_loss'])
val_loss3 = min(history3.history['val_loss'])

# Determine the best model based on the lowest validation loss
best_model_index = np.argmin([val_loss1, val_loss2, val_loss3])
best_model = models[best_model_index]
best_model_label = labels[best_model_index]

print(f"The best model is Model {best_model_index + 1}: {best_model_label} with a validation loss of {min([val_loss1, val_loss2, val_loss3])}")

The best model is Model 1: Simpler network with a validation loss of 0.21119742095470428

Avoiding overfitting¶

We will try few different techniques to avoid overfitting:

  • Early stopping
  • Dropout
  • L2 regularization
  • Smaller model

Then we will compare the results to determine the best model to use as the final model.

After this we will train the model one last time with the validation sets combined, and evaluate it with the test set.

In [31]:
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dropout
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping
from tensorflow.keras.regularizers import l2
from tensorflow.keras.layers import BatchNormalization

# Define early stopping callback
early_stopping = EarlyStopping(patience=300, restore_best_weights=True, monitor='val_mae')

# Modify the best model to include dropout layers
final_model = Sequential([
    Input(shape=(8,)),
    Dense(64, activation='relu'),
    BatchNormalization(),
    Dropout(0.5),
    Dense(25, activation='relu'), # 25 was best
    BatchNormalization(),
    Dropout(0.5),
    Dense(1)
])

# Compile model
final_model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='mse', metrics=['mae'])

# Fit model
history_final = final_model.fit(x_train, y_train, epochs=1000, batch_size=32, validation_data=(x_val, y_val), callbacks=[early_stopping])

Conclusion¶

Adding batchnormalizatio and dropout to the model with 2 hidden layers and slightly decreaseing the number of neurons in the hidden layers seems to be the best model.

We will train this model one last time with the validation sets combined and evaluate it with the test set.
